    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-08-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-08-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="119"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d119">
                <head>119. Draft Letter From President <persName corresp="#p_THS1" type="from"
                        >Truman</persName> to Attorney General <persName corresp="#p_CTC1" type="to"
                        >Clark</persName>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d119fn0">Source: Central Intelligence Agency
                        Records, Job 83–00764R, Box 1, Folder 5. No classification marking.
                        According to <ref target="#d122">Document 122</ref>, the letter was drafted
                        by Secretary to the National Intelligence Authority <persName
                            corresp="#p_LJSJ1">Lay</persName> and approved by all members on the
                        understanding that it would be sent if necessary. It appears that the draft
                        was never used.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-08-07"
                        >August 7, 1946</date>.</dateline>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. Attorney General:</hi> Under date of August 8,
                    1946, the members of the National Intelligence Authority communicated to you a
                    request that the Federal Bureau of Investigation personnel presently charged
                    with intelligence coverage in Latin America be retained at their <pb facs="0318"
                        n="290" xml:id="pg_290"/> posts until the representatives of the Central
                    Intelligence Group can take over in an orderly and efficient manner.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d119fn1">
                        <ref target="#d120">Document 120</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>It is my desire that in the national interest this request be granted.</p>
                <p>Sincerely,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_THS1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Harry S. Truman</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="2" xml:id="d119fn2">Printed from a copy that bears this typed
                            signature.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
